{"@context":"http://iiif.io/api/presentation/3/context.json","id":"https://digbmc.github.io/pta-manifests/phan/phan-15715/manifest.json","type":"Manifest","label":{"none":["PHAN-15715"]},"metadata":[{"label":{"none":["Timestamp"]},"value":{"none":["1:57:15"]}},{"label":{"none":["Film"]},"value":{"none":["Phantom Thread"]}},{"label":{"none":["Distance"]},"value":{"none":["medium shot"]}},{"label":{"none":["Angle"]},"value":{"none":["low"]}},{"label":{"none":["Location"]},"value":{"none":["interior"]}},{"label":{"none":["Movement"]},"value":{"none":["fixed"]}},{"label":{"none":["Composition"]},"value":{"none":["dirty single"]}}],"summary":{"none":["Man holds fork and knife in his hands as woman watches"]},"thumbnail":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-15715/tiles/full/300,169/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":169,"width":300}],"homepage":[{"id":"PHAN-15715","type":"Text","format":"text/html","label":{"none":["Object homepage"]}}],"items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-15715/canvas/1","type":"Canvas","height":1080,"width":1920,"label":{"none":["PHAN-15715"]},"thumbnail":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-15715/tiles/full/300,169/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":169,"width":300}],"items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-15715/canvas/1/annopage-1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-15715/canvas/1/annopage-1/anno-1","type":"Annotation","motivation":"painting","target":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-15715/canvas/1","body":{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-15715/tiles/full/1920,1080/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":1080,"width":1920,"service":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-15715/tiles","type":"ImageService3","profile":"http://iiif.io/api/image/3/level0.json"}]}}]}],"annotations":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-15715/canvas/1/page/p1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-15715/canvas/1/691a2d0a-871f-4ea5-88d3-af3432ae572e","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2026-06-30T17:15:47.837Z","creator":"Ada ","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>The carving visible in the background appears to be three soldiers, carrying weapons and a banner. Their armor and weaponry represent Alma’s battle to be fully a part of Reynolds’s life. They are all working together to carry the banner—a textile like those Reynolds works with—signaling the changes in the house of Woodcock and his equal partnership with Alma.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>"}],"target":{"type":"SpecificResource","source":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-15715/canvas/1","selector":{"type":"FragmentSelector","conformsTo":"http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/","value":"xywh=pixel:448.9055023923445,261.32700358851673,394.02586722488036,376.8480861244019"}}},{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-15715/canvas/1/36030191-b4c5-45e8-84be-58b1fe4e74fd","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2026-06-30T17:16:25.435Z","creator":"Ada ","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>Sophie Lewis reads <em>Phantom Thread</em> as a pessimistic statement on heterosexual love, marriage, and class relations: “<em>Phantom Thread </em>is a morbid depiction of social reproduction, where the gender division of labor appears as a toxic metabolism or circuit of necrotic value. The brutal poison of reification flows forth from Reynolds, attacking Alma’s body, and returns back again in the form of a deadly mushroom, penetrating Reynolds. This is, surely, the core thought of the movie and its most devastating: that the thrill of interpersonal love is only possible within coupled heterosexuality if the violence emanating from each party can be balanced so as to enable <em>respect </em>subtended by exclusion (a joint future as wedded bourgeois subjects, exploiting unwed feminized laborers)” (Lewis, “<a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" class=\"Hyperlink SCXW247372616 BCX4\" href=\"https://blindfieldjournal.com/2018/02/09/fuck-off-to-back-where-you-came-from-notes-on-the-phantom-thread/\"><u>‘Fuck Off to Back Where You Came From’</u></a>”).&nbsp;</p>"}],"target":{"type":"SpecificResource","source":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-15715/canvas/1","selector":{"type":"FragmentSelector","conformsTo":"http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/","value":"xywh=pixel:95.27063397129183,70.9046052631578,313.5062799043061,241.4982057416268"}}}]}]}]}